Despite their herculean effort, England could not find a final try and finished second in the championship, behind Ireland. 

After the match, England head coach Stuart Lancaster praised his side for 'one of the most courageous performances' he has seen from his side.

'It will go down as one of the great games of rugby,' he added. 

Earlier in the day, Ireland thrashed 40-10 in Edinburgh to mark a dismal campaign for the Scots and an impressive Wales ran riot in Rome, thumping Italy 61-20.  

All smiles: The fourth-in-line to the throne grins alongside students from Reigate School, in Surrey 

Before England's crunch match against France, Prince Harry had met girls from Reigate School and The Quest Academy, Croydon, who had played in the warm-up game.

Harry - who is a Vice Patron of the Rugby Football Union (RFU) - also chatted with members of the armed forces at Twickenham . 

Looking dapper in his navy suit, the fourth-in-line to the throne then took his seat in the stand before singing the national anthem with gusto. 

